{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580928/1945083101/0294.xml":{"full_text":"So Labor\nMay Know\nOPEN LETTER TO SENATORS\nTAFT AND BURTON, AND SOME\nOHIO CONGRESSMEN:\nGentlemen:\nWe the people of Ohio are some\nwhat amazed by your antics in the\npast few months. We are suddenly\nmade aware (1) of your abysmal ig\nnorance or (2) otkr clear foresight. It\nstuns us to think' that we, the people,\nsaw all this coming and you did not.\nWe speak, of course, of our plan\nless reconversion period. While we\nwere shouting in our Union halls and\nour. little gatherings about the \u201cim\npending catastrophe\u201d/ you dismissed\nour fears with a light \u201cnothing to it at\nall.\u201d While we urged action\u2014a plan\nfor Peace\u2014you favored inaction.\nWe the people are particularly dis\nturbed by the way you treated the\nNational Planning Resources Board.\nYou knocked that one out four years\nago, saying at the time that planning\nfor the peace was \u201cvisionary\u201d and\n\"unrealistic\u201d. Overriding protests of\nthe late President Roosevelt, you re\nfused: to continue the Board. Now,\nwe ask, who was right\u2014you or Roose\nvelt? Are you prepared to take re\nsponsibility for killing the Planning\nand Resources Board?\ny/t the people also woyld like you\nto explain your recent votes on Re\nciprocal Trade, excessive profits,\nOPA, and other bills designed to aid\nthe common man. We would like to\nknow why you failed to pass the Full\nEmployment Bill, the Minimum Wage\nBill, and the improved social security\nmeasure taking instead a two\nmonth\u2019s vacation.\nWe should like to ask you if you\nWere aware Congress has taken care\npf Industry through rec.onvcrson (tax\nrebates) anf( agriculture (parity\nprices) but has refused any guaran\ntee for Labor? Surely you must know\nthese things because \\vc, the un-in\nformcd ppople, are aware of them.\nIn vievf of the foregoing, we the\npeople tjpust accuse you of totally\nlacking yny grasp of the needs and\nsentiments of the people whom you\npurportedly represent. As a conse\nquence we give you fair warning that\nunless your record changes and\nswiftly\u2014you won\u2019t be voting your\nself any mote two month\u2019s vacations.\nOr maybe that\u2019s talking through our\nhat\u00bb too, huh?\nRegretfully,\nSIX MILLION OHIO WORK*\n-:E)\u00bb\"AW\u00a5kE!^T>cmTEs;\nJ\u00bb S. For your infortnation, the fol\nlowing measure* help point the way\nto an orderly reconversion:\n1. Adequate unemployment com\npensation, Finance Committee hear\nings start August 28 on S1274. insur\ning up to $25 a week for 26 weeks.\n2. Full Employment. House Bank\ning and Currency Sub-Committee\nhearings resume August 21; report\ndue September 5. House co-spon\nsors should pass majority mark be\nfore hearings start about September\n20.\n3. Raise minimum wage to 65c\nnow, 75c in two years and extend\ncoverage, S1282,\n4. A million homes a yyar for 10\nyears. Wagner-Ellender Housing Bill,\nintroduced last day before recess.\nSI 342.\n5, Repeal rider breaking U. S. Em\nployment Service into 51 State pieces\n90 days after the war. More funds for\nUSES.\n6. Permanent FEPC, S101.\n7. Big funds for public works, both\nfor planning and construction.\n8. Streamline Surplus War Prpper\nty Act (But look out for fast plays.)\n9. MVA and other TVA-type re\ngional development plans.\n10. Appropriations to make good\npledge to farmers of support prices\ni for 2 years after end of war.\n11. Wagner-Murray Dingell Bill\nextending Social Security.\n12. Federal Aid to Education.\n13. Hill-Burton Bill for $100 mil\nlion a year construction of health cen\nters, et cetera.\n14. Aiken-LaFollette food allot\nment Bill. Also School lunch bill.\n15. Cleaning up of GI GYP (\u201cBUI\nof Rights.\u201d)\nGovernor May Act\nA CIO delegation called on Gover\nnor Lausche this week to summon the\nLegislature back into session. Thou\nsands of Ohio workers, entitled to un\nemployment compensation, at present\nmust draw benefits on basis, of old\nlaw ($16 for 18 weeks) instead of new\nlaw which goes into effect October\n12 ($21 for 22 weeks). The CIO del\negation asked the Governor to call the\nLegislature to secure permission to\nmake the new law immediately appli\ncable. The Governor said he would\nthink it over.\nA CIO delegation also plans a\n(Continued on Page 3)\nONE\nFOR ALL\n'W \u2018S' |r: 7 v\n*/-\u25a0\"H-7 -V-\u25a0\u25a0'\u2022..,\u25a0\u2022 r-:\u2022 s,.v: ,/v.-, .,v\nfFICIAL PUBLICATION OF ORGANIZED LABOR IN AKRON AND VICINITY\nt f, Js V\" ,.v\nCooperate* With 4. F. of b. and CIO Labor Union* of Summit, Medina, PortAge, Wayne end Surrounding Countie* Member of International Labor Prat* of A\nALL FOR\nONE I\nVol. 23 No. 34\nAKRON, OHIO, FRIDAY, AUGUST 31,1945\n$2.00 PER YEAR\nBy Philip Murray, President\nCongress of Industrial Organizations\nOn Labor Day, 1945, labor shares the pride of'all Americans in\nthe magnificent recbrd of our armed forces, as signalized by the\ncomplete defeat of the Japanese and the Nazis and the smashing\nblows dealt to the Japanese aggres\nsors. Labor has contributed to these\nsuccesses.\nIn the sphere of international rela\ntions, labor has also done its part for\nthe continuing unity of the United\nNations. The San Francisco Charter\nhas laid a firm foundation for world\norganization against fascism, aggres\nsion and future war, while the World\nConference of Trade Unions has made\nsplendid progress in uniting the work\n:ng people of all countries of these\nand other common purposes.\nLiut on the domestic scene, un\nfortunately, American labor finds\nfewer grounds for satisfaction.\nIn its unparalleled war achieve\nments, America has shown a capacity\nfor organization and production that\n-hould assure the full employment of\n>tir people after the war in creating\nunparalleled prosperity \u201cfot \u2018all. But,\nwith reconversion already under way,\nthere are many tragic signs that sel\nfish privilege and government inertia\nare obstructing the fulfillment\u2018of this\npromise, .y-.. i,,..\nT fuf* mass'' purcfiawtitg\"'\u201d t>i>W^r -'w\nAmerican working people must' obvi\nously be\" one of the main pillars of\nCIO and AFL Members\nTo United in End of\nWar Festivities\nOrganized Labor of Akron\u2014AFL and CIO\u2014plan a huge cele\nbration on September 30th to mark the end of the war with Japan.\nThe proposed program was given the approval of Akron Indus\ntrial Union Council at their regular business meeting last Friday\nnight. The Trades and Labor Assembly of Summit County will take\nup the matter at its business meeting 1\nscheduled Jor Thursday night.\nPreliminary plans provide for a\nhuge parade in which Labor indus\ntries, merchants and civic and frater\nnal organizations will participate.\nStreet dancing and other entertain\nment will be included.\nScores of floats, representing all of\nAkron\u2019s industries, will be in the pa\nrade, according to preliminary plans\nbeing made for the affair. An appro\npriation of $250 has been voted by\ndelegates of Akron Industrial Union\nCouncil to pay half of the cost of a\nLabor-sponsored float with the Amer\nican Federation of Labor.\nAIUC NOTICE\nThe next regular business meet\ning of Akron Industrial Union\nCouncil will be held in the auditor\nium of Goodrich Local, United\nRubber Workers of America, 708\nSouth Main street, on Friday night,\nSeptember 14th. President F. B.\nVan Houten will call the meeting\nto order at 7:30 o\u2019clock. This an\nnouncement constitutes the official\nnotice of the meeting to all Coun\ncil delegates and other persons de\nsiring to attend the meeting.\nThe next regular meeting of the\nOrganization Committee will be\nheld in the Council\u2019s offices, 714\nSouth Main street, on Wednesday\nsight, September 12th. The meet\ning is scheduled for 7:30 o\u2019clock.\nThe Executive Committee of the\nCouncil will hold its next regular\nmeeting in the Council\u2019s offices on\nThursday night, September 13th.\nour postwar prosperity. Yet today\nthis purchasing power is being cruelly\nslashed by lauoffs, loss of overtime,\ndowngrading mid generally reduced\ntake-home pay, while the infamous\nincubus of the Little Steel formula\nsmothers collective bargaining and\nholds wage rates far below sky-high\nliving costs.\nCongress meanwhile has been eager\nand quick to provide profit guarantees\nand other protections for business in\nreconversion, but ljas riot lifted a\nfinger to aid the worst victims of re\nconversion, the laid-ofl war workers.\nThere is also a lamentable lack of\nnational planning for full employ\nment, and a tendency to lift produc\ntion and price controls in such a way\naa to restore the \u201cnormalcy\u201d of un\nlimited grabbing for the few and de\npression an'd unemployment for- the\nmany.\nIn this Labor Day, the CIO calls\nupon our political and industrial lead-\ners to join with labor and the whole\nVttriiican.:-Wi\u2014tfcrersin g -these\ndisastrous trends before it js too late.\n(Continued on Page Two)\nThe celebration, according to pre\nliminary plans, will he one of the\ngreatest in Akron\u2019s history. The pa\nrade is expected to surpass those\nconducted during Akron\u2019s centenial\ncelebration and for the opening of the\nXorth hill viaduct over 20 years ago.\nFinal plans for the celebration will\nhe discussed at the meeting of Akron\nIndustrial Union Council slated for\nSeptember 14th.\nDemand Better\nBus Service\nThe complete restoration of bus\nand street car service in Akron to its\npre-war status was demanded by Ak\nron Industrial Union Council at its\nbusiness meeting last Friday night. A\nresolution approved at the session\npointed out that wartime restrictions\nno longer are needed and that service\nat the present time is entirely inade\nquate.\nA general survey of Akron\u2019s trans\nportation system was advocated to\ndetermine just what changes should\nbe made in routes covered and the\nduration of time between buses. Ak\nron City Council is being requested\nto enter the picture and to demand\nalso that service be improved.\nThe Office of Defense Transporta\ntion requested cuts in Akron\u2019s bus\nservice as a war economy measure. A\nskip-stop order was made and various\nlines were shortened. Changes pro\nposed by Akron Industrial Union\nCouncil would restore all vacated\nstops and extend lines tc their pre-war\nlength.\nBy Shekman H. Dalrymple, President\ntynited Rubber Workers of America\nLabor throughout the United States should be greteful for the\nopportunity to'celebrate Labor Day knowing that the terrible and\nmuch dreaded rfrar has been concluded. We must now turn our minds\nand our efforts- toward the problem of reconversion prepar&tory to\nproducing gohdji essential to our American way of life and for the\nbenefit of t(ie peoples of the world.'\nWage earners of this country have\ngone a long way;; since that first La*\nbor Day celebration in 1882. In those\nyears the working people were figura\ntively battling wsh their bare hands\nagainst a powerful, well-entrenched\nenemy. Our first effective weapons\nwere given us during President\nRoosevelt\u2019s first administration. Since\nthen labor has been accorded a higher\ndegree of participation in the social,\neconomic and industrial life of our\ncountry.\nWe should take inventory and\nmeditate a hit upon the working con\nditions and wape rates of all the\nworkers whom ifre are privileged to\nrepresent in order that we will be in\na position to take, the necessary steps\nto correct any injustices or any in\nequities which may exist.\nLabor representatives must take the\nnecessary steps .to retain the gains\nmade by labor ip the face of ever\n_present opgosi^gyC must: use our\norganizational influence and facilities\nto bring about legislation that will\nserve to the best interests of all of the\nA LABOR DAY MESSAGE\nBy RUTH TAYLOR\nUnionism is a road, not a destination. It is a way, not an end.\nLike a road, unionism has its ups and downs, its hills and valleys, its\nbypaths, its detours.\nUnionism is something incomprehensible to those who do not\nknow Democracy. They cannot imagine a road conforming to the\ncontour of the land\u2014their highways must smash through in geo\nmetric lines. They cannot imagine a way of life that conforms itself\nto and serves the people who compose it. Their way of life must\nsmash through the lives of subjects compressing them ruthlessly to\none set pattern. The greatest handicap of tyrants is their lack of\nimagination, their lack of the realization that a man will do more\nbecause he wants to, than he will because he is told to.\nUnionism gains its strength from voluntary cooperation a\nunity of purpose and action. It does not demand of its followers\nthat they must all think alike, any more than that all roads must be\nalike. It does however call for a spirit of cohesion on all fundamen\ntal principles. To be a vital force unionism must be based upon mu\ntual understanding and must be motivated by mutual ideals, or prin\nciples.\nThe principles of trade unionism are the same as those of De\nmocracy\u2014the right of free men to organize, to associate with their\nfellow men in action for the common good, to speak freely and with\nout fear, and to act according to their own conscience.\nThe greatest protection against totalitarianism, whether of the\nleft or right, is a strong, organized, self-disciplined labor unionism\ndedicated to a high purpose. Self-discipline is what differentiates\nfree labor from the forced labor of dictator-ruled states.\nUnionism is not perfect. No growing thing is complete. No or\nganization composed of men is without the imperfections of men.\nBut unionism is a road toward cooperation, toward the ideal of un\nselfish working together for the common good.\nThose who believe in unionism have a task before them. They\nmust prove the ability of free men to construct a world in which all\nmen are free from fear and want. If they cannot do that, then they\nhave failed the cause of unionism\u2014but they will not fail.\nKenneth Cole, CIO Organiber,\nDies lln Washington\nThe de&th of Kenneth Cole, pioneer\nCIO organizer in Ohio, and more re\ncently a member of the UAW-CIO\nWashington staff, was reported this\nweek. His death brought immediate\nresponses of grief from members of\nall organized Labor.\nCole made his reputation on March\n10, 1937, when he and 12 other men\nrepresenting nine Internationals which\nhad been suspended from the AFL\npeople and oppose any and all legis\nlation that is not destined to better\nthe conditions of the workers of our\ncountry. VVe must champion the\nrights of all groups of the common\npeople and avoid restricting our vis\nion to narrow exclusive labor clian\nnels. We must consistently seek eco\nnomic improvements fot the workers\nin the same degree that businessmen\nare continually striving for higher\nprofits and lower production costs.\nMany problems will arise during\nthe post-war days which will require\nthe attention of labor, management\nand government. Team work will be\nessential in formulating and applying\nproper applications to many of the\nproblems in order that the present\nand future welfare of our people be'\nassured. Labor and management1\nmust cooperate and work together in\nthe planning for reconversion in order\nthat conversion from wartime produc\ntion to. <Uyiliwii. production nuy be \u00abk\npeSited so that unempfoymenr'dtie \\o\nreconversion will be minimized.\n(Continued on Page Tlireel\nbecause of. their desire tc organize un\nskilled workers, met at Local 12 head\nquarters in Toledo. Out of that meet\ning grew the first Industrial Union\nCouncil in the country.' At their first\nregular meeting the Council members\nmade formal application for a CIO\ncharter, and temporary officers .were\nelected. Cole was chosen as Executive\nSecretary at that time, a position\n(Continued on Page Two)\nBy George R. Bass, Ex. Secretary\nAkron Industrial Union Council\nAgain we observe another Labor Day, after having failed to ob\nserve the day set aside' to commemorate Labor, for three or four\nyears during the war with Germany and Japan, only so recently eitd-\u2022\ned in Victory for the allies, if it can be called a Victory. V\nFailing to observe Labor Day i\u00ab\nonly one more privilege Labor was\nwilling to give op to be able to win\nthe war. In that great conflict Labor\ngave everything and were glad to be\nable to contribute to the winning of\nthe war, and now we come to the job\nof establishing the peace.\nLabor played such a large part in\nthe winning of the war. now they\nshould be considered largely in a just\npeace. A nation cannot long with\nstand unemployment and lack of earn\nings. Cannot long endure a low in\ncome or prosper with half of its citi\nzens unemployed and underpaid, with\na low standard of living. Consequent\nly there can be no peace as long as\nthese things are in evidence, so on this\nSeptember 3. 1945. Labor after having\nso amply demonstrated how great a\npart she can and wants to play in the\npreservation and perpetuation of our\nnation, urges all American to contrib\nute everything possible to bring about\na peace that will long endure so there\nwill be 60 recurrence of this last liolo--.\ncaust.\nSigned:\nGeorge R. Bass, Exec. Sec AIUC.\nSen. Thomas To Speak\nAt Summit Park\nPark Labor Day\n\n\nt\nV.*\nU. S. Senator A. D. Thomas of Oklahoma, one of America\u2019s sen?,\nior statesmen in the halls of Congress \"\u2019ho affectionately is known\nas Labor\u2019s Own Champion, will he the speaker at the Labor Day\ncelebration Monday at Summit Beach Park.\n-.U.\nfeS\nWMC Is Urged\nTo Dissolve\nAkron Industrial Union Council\nwent on record at its business meeting\nlast Friday night in favor of the area\nWar Manpower Commission, headed\nby Harry C. Markle, dissolving imme\ndiately.\nThe resolution pointed out that the\naera War Manpower Commission was\nsimply a war-time body and that ;t\ncompleted its work with the end of\nthe war with Japan. CIO delegates to\nthe commission were requested in the\nresolution to vote for the immediate\nending of the commission at the next\nmeeting of the commissiou.\n(Continued on Page 3)\nWeekly Labor\nRadio Shows\nUnited Rubber Workers of\nAmerica will broadcast a program\neach Wednesday evening at 6:30\nover Radio Station WHKK, Ak\nron, 640 on your dials, for the en\ntertainment and education of all\nlisteners in the greater Akron area.\nThe program will be transcribed\nand repeated each Wednesday\nnight at 10:30 o\u2019clock. It is a\nworth-while program. Listen to it\neach Wednesday.\nThe \u201cAFL Radio Show\u201d is a\nregular Saturday night feature of\nRadio Station WAKR. It comes\non the air at 6:45 and lasts until\n7 o\u2019clock. It is a very good pro\ngram. Listen to it regularly.\nLausche Asked\nTo CaN Ohio\nf*\nv;\nLegislature\nV rl,,.\nGovernor\n|I\nA resolution calling on\nLausche to call -a special sessiot). Of\nthe Ohio General Assembly at oncj\nto consider an increase in Unemptoyy,\nment Compensation was approved\nunanimously last Friday night \u2019by:\nAkron Industrial Union Council.\nThe resolution, which was approved\noriginally by members of Goodyear\nLocal No. 2, United Rubber Workers'\nof America, points out the fact that\nthousands of war workers now unem\nployed because of war contract. can-,\ncellations cannot collect increased unA,\nemployment compensation until Qcy*\ntober 12. The making of increased'\n\u25a0fl\nv:\n\nunemployment payment retroactive'\nuntil August 14th. the date on which\nthe war with Japan..ended, is,urged.\ncreased unemployment. compensation..\n{Continued on Page 2)\nf Declining to come to Akron tor tne\naddress until after he had received'the\nword of President Truman that t^\ntrip would not delay the nation\u2019s\nconversion program. Senator ThomkS\nwas not able until late in the week to\nnotify Akron Labor leaders that he\nwould be able to fill the speaking date,,\nWith service in Congress sinqe\n1907, Senator Thomas indeed is oa^\nof the nation\u2019s senior Legislators. His\nlong record of service has been\nmarked by his support of all major\nLabor legislation that has been intro\nduced. V\nHundreds of members of Organized\nLabor of Akron\u2014AFL and CIO\u2014are\nexpected to be at Summit Beach Park\nto hear the senator\u2019s address sched\nuled for 3 o\u2019clock. The talk will deal\nwith reconversion problems of the na\ntion as they pertain to members of\nLabor.\nAlthough the hbur of Senator\nThomas\u2019 arrival in Akron has not yet\nbeen announced, it has been assured\nthat he will be at the Mayflower hotel\nto receive Akron Labor leaders unper\nson during the day ar.d to discuss\ntheir problems with them. -J -T\nBecause of his seniority. in tin\nUnited States Senate, Senator Thomas\nholds many important committee as\nsignments, including the chairmanship\nof the important War Appropriations\nCommittee. Akron is indeed consid\nered fortunate to have the services of\nsuch a national figure in its annual\nLabor Day program. V.\nStarting at 10 o\u2019clock; Monday\nmorning, there will not be a dull tain-,\nute at Summit Beach park. The,fe\nwill be contests and races of all ldnd|s\nfor men, women and children. Prizes\n(Continued on Page Two)<\nBRING THE BOYS\n\\r. \\x ,s 1 \u20224 i\n,7\n\u2018-*1\nr:\nV>\nfv.\nBACK BUY BONDS\n../Vi\nm\ni\n:r.'1, v\n..?5","height":"27396","width":"21596"}}
